# Always reload PHP-FPM

After you **change** **`index.php`** or **`config.php`** (the deployed FormatForge app), treat the task as **unfinished** until **PHP-FPM has been reloaded** on the Linux host so **opcache** picks up the new code.

## Run on the host

1. **`php -l`** on the file you edited (syntax check).
2. **`sudo systemctl reload php8.3-fpm`** — or the unit that matches the pool socket (**`scripts/align-php-fpm-socket.sh`**, **`ls /run/php/*.sock`**: `php8.2-fpm` / `php8.4-fpm` when applicable).

**nginx-only** edits do not require FPM reload; use the nginx rule. **PHP edits** require FPM reload even if nginx was not touched.

If **`sudo`** or **`systemctl`** are unavailable in the agent environment, run what you can and **explicitly** tell the operator which **`systemctl reload …`** command still must run on the server.
